SCPCL000824 - Using SingleR for classification of tumor cells

Ally Hawkins

2024-07-02

Introduction

This notebook looks at using SingleR to annotate tumor cells in SCPCL000824. We used three different references with SingleR:

  1. Blueprint: Both the full BlueprintEncodeData reference from celldex and SCPCL000822 where cells are either annotated as tumor or normal. Ambiguous cells are removed from SCPCL000822.
  2. Original: SCPCL000822 where all tumor cells are labeled as tumor and all other cells keep the original annotation obtained from running SingleR as part of scpca-nf.
  3. Original and Blueprint: SCPCL000822 with tumor cells labeled as in #2 combined with the full BlueprintEncodeData reference.

Setup

suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  # load required packages
  library(SingleCellExperiment)
  library(ggplot2)
})

# Set default ggplot theme
theme_set(
  theme_bw()
)

# quiet messages
options(readr.show_col_types = FALSE)
ComplexHeatmap::ht_opt(message = FALSE)
# The base path for the OpenScPCA repository, found by its (hidden) .git directory
repository_base <- rprojroot::find_root(rprojroot::is_git_root)

# The current data directory, found within the repository base directory
data_dir <- file.path(repository_base, "data", "2024-05-01")
sample_dir <- file.path(data_dir, "SCPCP000015", "SCPCS000492")

# The path to this module
module_base <- file.path(repository_base, "analyses", "cell-type-ewings")
# source in helper functions: plot_gene_heatmap() and plot_cnv_heatmap() 
# create_classification_df() and create_marker_gene_df()
validation_functions <- file.path(module_base, "scripts", "utils", "tumor-validation-helpers.R")
source(validation_functions)

# source in helper functions for make_jaccard_matrix() and jaccard()
jaccard_functions <- file.path(module_base, "scripts", "utils", "jaccard-functions.R")
source(jaccard_functions)
# Input files
sce_file <- file.path(sample_dir, "SCPCL000824_processed.rds")
marker_genes_file <- file.path(module_base, "references", "tumor-marker-genes.tsv")

# annotations from SCPCL000824_tumor-gene-expression-exploration.Rmd
annotations_dir <- file.path(module_base, "results", "annotation_tables", "SCPCS000492")
annotations_file <- file.path(annotations_dir, "SCPCL000824_tumor-classifications.tsv.gz")

# gene set scores to use for validation 
results_dir <- file.path(module_base, "results", "annotate_tumor_cells_output", "SCPCS000492")
geneset_scores_file <- file.path(results_dir, "SCPCL000824_gene-set-scores.tsv")

# singler results 
full_singler_results <- file.path(module_base, "scratch", "SingleR", "SCPCL000824_singler-results.rds")
singler_annotations_file <- file.path(annotations_dir, "SCPCL000824_singler-classifications.tsv.gz")
# read in sce file 
sce <- readr::read_rds(sce_file)

# read in annotations
annotations_df <- readr::read_tsv(annotations_file)
singler_annotations_df <- readr::read_tsv(singler_annotations_file)

# read in full singler results 
singler_results_list <- readr::read_rds(full_singler_results)

# read in gene set scores
geneset_scores_df <- readr::read_tsv(geneset_scores_file)
# generate classification df to use for plots 
classification_df <- sce |> 
  scuttle::makePerCellDF(use.dimred = "UMAP") |> 
  # replace UMAP.1 with UMAP1
  dplyr::rename_with(
    \(x) stringr::str_replace(x, "^UMAP\\.", "UMAP")
  ) |>
  # get rid of excess columns
  dplyr::select(barcodes, UMAP1, UMAP2, singler_celltype_annotation) |> 
  # join with previous annotations, singler results, and gene set scores 
  dplyr::left_join(annotations_df, by = c("barcodes" = "cell_barcode")) |> 
  dplyr::left_join(singler_annotations_df, by = "barcodes") |> 
  dplyr::left_join(geneset_scores_df, by = "barcodes") |>
  # get the top cell types for each classification method for plotting later 
  dplyr::mutate(
    across(
      ends_with("_classification"),
      \(x) {
        x |>
          # there are warnings because we have some that have less than 7 cell types (ones that only did tumor/normal)
          # this is why we ignore warnings in this chunk 
          forcats::fct_lump_n(7, other_level = "All remaining cell types", ties.method = "first") |>
          forcats::fct_infreq() |>
          forcats::fct_relevel("All remaining cell types", after = Inf)
      },
      .names = "{.col}_lumped"
    )
  )

SingleR results

UMAPs of cell assignments

The first thing we will do is look at the annotated cell types on a UMAP. The top 7 cell types are shown for each reference used and all other cells are lumped together.

# list of columns with singler results for UMAPs
singler_annotation_columns <- c(
  "blueprint_tumor_classification_lumped",
  "updated_singler_classification_lumped",
  "updated_singler_blueprint_classification_lumped"
) |> 
  purrr::set_names("Blueprint", "Original", "Original + Blueprint")

singler_annotation_columns |> 
  purrr::imap(\(annotation_column, title){
    ggplot(
    classification_df,
    aes(x = UMAP1, y = UMAP2, color = .data[[annotation_column]])
  ) +
    # set points for all "other" points
    geom_point(
      data = dplyr::select(
        classification_df, -.data[[annotation_column]]
      ),
      color = "gray80",
      alpha = 0.5,
      size = 0.5
    ) +
    # set points for desired cell type
    geom_point(size = 0.5, alpha = 0.5) +
    facet_wrap(
      vars(.data[[annotation_column]]),
      ncol = 3
    ) +
    scale_color_brewer(palette = "Dark2") +
    # remove axis numbers and background grid
    scale_x_continuous(labels = NULL, breaks = NULL) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = NULL, breaks = NULL) +
    guides(
      color = guide_legend(
        title = title,
        # more visible points in legend
        override.aes = list(
          alpha = 1,
          size = 1.5
        )
      )
    )
  })

It appears that most cells in that bottom group of cells are being called tumor cells regardless of the reference that is used. The major differences here are in how the normal cells are labeled. For right now, lets focus on just identifying the tumor cells and see how similar each of the references are to each other before we look into normal cells and compare to the other methods that we have used.

Compare tumor cell annotations between between SingleR references used

First we will just look at the overlap in the tumor cells between all three methods.

tumor_cells <- list(
  "Blueprint" = classification_df$barcodes[classification_df$blueprint_tumor_classification == "Tumor"],
  "Original" = classification_df$barcodes[classification_df$updated_singler_classification == "Tumor"],
  "Original and Blueprint" = classification_df$barcodes[classification_df$updated_singler_blueprint_classification == "Tumor"]
)

UpSetR::upset(UpSetR::fromList(tumor_cells), order.by = "freq") |> print()

Generally, it looks like there is a large group of cells that are identified as tumor regardless of the reference, with a few cells that are specifically tumor in only one or two references.

Lets see where the shared cells are and if they are where we would expect them to be based on marker gene expression plots we made previously (bottom right group of cells).

classification_df <- classification_df |> 
  dplyr::mutate(singler_consensus_call = dplyr::case_when(
    blueprint_tumor_classification == "Tumor" & updated_singler_classification == "Tumor" & updated_singler_blueprint_classification == "Tumor" ~ "Tumor",
    blueprint_tumor_classification == "Tumor" | updated_singler_classification == "Tumor" | updated_singler_blueprint_classification == "Tumor" ~ "Ambiguous",
    .default = "Normal"
  )) 

ggplot(classification_df, aes(x = UMAP1, y = UMAP2, color = singler_consensus_call)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, size = 0.5)

It looks like the cells that are normal are in the smaller clusters and the larger cluster is mostly tumor cells with some that are ambiguous across SingleR references. This is what I would expect given the marker gene expression in these cells.

Compare normal cell annotations between references used

Next we will compare all of the top cell types identified in each method to the top cell types identified in the other methods. This will show us the overlap in tumor cells and normal cell types identified.

methods <- c(
  "updated_singler_classification_lumped",
  "updated_singler_blueprint_classification_lumped"
) |> 
  purrr::set_names("Original", "Original and Blueprint")

# compare blueprint to original and origintal + blueprint
plot_jaccard(classification_df,
             annotation_column = "blueprint_tumor_classification_lumped",
             methods_to_compare = methods,
             column_title = "Blueprint",
             legend_match = "Original") |> 
  ComplexHeatmap::draw(
    heatmap_legend_side = "right",
    # add a margin to the heatmap so labels don't get cut off
    padding = unit(c(2, 20, 2, 2), "mm")
  )

# compare original to original + blueprint
plot_jaccard(classification_df,
             annotation_column = "updated_singler_classification_lumped",
             methods_to_compare = c("Original and Blueprint" = "updated_singler_blueprint_classification_lumped"),
             column_title = "Original",
             legend_match = "Original")

A few things that we see in these plots:

  • There seems to be mostly consensus across all three methods on which cells are tumor cells, which is consistent with the upset plot.
  • When only using Blueprint, a lot of cells are categorized as Normal. This means they match the non-tumor cells identified in SCPCL000822 more than they match the normal cell types in the Blueprint reference. Additionally, with only Blueprint, there is a group of cells that are called as tumor but actually appear to match endothelial cells present in SCPCL000822.
  • The cells that arent called as either Tumor or Normal in the Blueprint only reference mostly match up to erythrocyte in the reference that just uses SCPCL000822 (original). These same cells match to their corresponding Blueprint cell type when combining SCPCL000822 and Blueprint (e.g., fibroblasts, neurons, and epithelial cells are identifed in both).
  • When comparing using just SCPCL000822 (original) to SCPCL000822 and Blueprint (original and blueprint), we see an overlap in endothelial cells and chrondrocytes. We also see that for the most part the top cell types identified are the same except when using blueprint you see the addition of epithelial cells.

Next, we will measure how well the updated classification matches the original SingleR class identified in SCPCL000824. We will create a confusion matrix between each of these SingleR references and the original SingleR classifications from scpca-nf. Note that we will not include tumor cells here and will only look at shared cell types that are identified in both. Any cells that are not in the shared cell types are classified as other.

For all matrices, the rows are the original SingleR annotations and the columns are from the new annotations.

singler_annotation_columns |> 
  purrr::map(\(classification_column){
    
    # first get list of tumor cells for this classificationn
    # we want to remove these since we are only interested in comparing normal cell types
    tumor_cells <- classification_df |> 
      dplyr::filter({{classification_column}} == "Tumor") |> 
      dplyr::pull(barcodes)
    
    # get list of shared cell types with SingleR
    original_celltypes <- classification_df$singler_celltype_annotation |> 
      unique()
    new_celltypes <- classification_df[[classification_column]] |> 
      unique()
    
    shared_celltypes <- intersect(original_celltypes, new_celltypes)
    
    caret_df <- classification_df |> 
      # first remove tumor cells 
      dplyr::filter(!barcodes %in% tumor_cells) |> 
      # then update to make sure all cell types are shared
      # anything not in shared cell types are classified as "other" 
      dplyr::mutate(singler_caret = dplyr::if_else(singler_celltype_annotation %in% shared_celltypes, singler_celltype_annotation, "Other"),
                    new_ref_caret = dplyr::if_else(!!sym(classification_column) %in% shared_celltypes, !!sym(classification_column), "Other"))
    
    caret::confusionMatrix(
      table(
        caret_df$singler_caret, 
        caret_df$new_ref_caret)
    )
    
  })

Here we see that the highest Kappa, although still very low, is with using the original SingleR annotations from SCPCL000822 and use of Blueprint. Generally, I would say there is not a lot of agreement with the original SingleR annotations. Identifying the correct classes of the normal cells I think is out of scope for this notebook and it is ultimately more important to identify a way to label tumor cells.

I tend to favor using one of these options:

  • Blueprint: SCPCL000822 with cells labeled as either tumor or normal in combination with Blueprint.
  • Original and Blueprint: SCPCL000822 with tumor cells labeled and all other cells labeled with the original SingleR annotations in combination with Blueprint.

I dont like using just the Original, where the only reference comes from a single sample, SCPCL000822. Its very likely that the types of normal cells will differ across samples, so I think we want to be able to use Blueprint to help classify any of those cells.

Another option would be to try running with just the tumor cells from SCPCL000822 as a reference in combination with Blueprint, removing the normal cells from the reference. But either of the above options I think would be sufficient to labeling and pulling out tumor cells. Lets confirm this by comparing to our previously used marker gene based methods for classifying this sample.

Compare tumor cell annotations with SingleR to marker gene based methods

Below we will compare the annotations obtained using the different references and SingleR to the marker gene based annotations identified in SCPCL000824_tumor-gene-expression-exploration.Rmd. First we will look at the Jaccard similarity between each of the SingleR references and all of the marker gene based methods. All cells will be categorized as either tumor or normal.

 original_methods <- c(
    "updated_marker_gene_classification",
    "auc_classification",
    "ucell_classification"
  ) |> 
  purrr::set_names("Marker genes", "AUCell", "UCell")

# heatmap comparing each singler annotation type to each of the marker gene based methods 
heatmap_list <- singler_annotation_columns |> 
  purrr::iwalk(\(annotation_column, name) {
    
    # first make singler annotations normal or tumor for easier visualization
    plot_df <- classification_df |> 
      dplyr::mutate(new_annotation = dplyr::if_else(!!sym(annotation_column) == "Tumor", "Tumor", "Normal"))
    
    plot_jaccard(
      classification_df = plot_df, 
      annotation_column = "new_annotation", 
      methods_to_compare = original_methods,
      column_title = name,
      legend_match = "UCell"
    ) |> 
      ComplexHeatmap::draw(
        heatmap_legend_side = "right",
        # add a margin to the heatmap so labels don't get cut off
        padding = unit(c(2, 20, 2, 2), "mm")
      )
  })

Generally, these methods agree on which cells are tumor cells.

It looks like using Blueprint alone is the most similar to all marker based methods. However, it looks like UCell categorizes more cells as normal that are classified as tumor with any of the SingleR methods.

For both original and original and blueprint, it looks like there is a good amount of cells that SingleR classifies as normal, but the marker gene based methods classify as tumor. This tells me that using SingleR may be slightly more conservative than the marker gene based methods.

Validate marker gene expression in SingleR annotations

The last thing we will do is confirm that the cells that are identified as tumor cells with SingleR have increased expression of marker genes and higher gene set scores. We would expect this to be the case, but we also want to see if we are missing calling any tumor cells that have higher gene expression.

For these plots we will also look at all the marker based classifications so we can compare across all options.

# first get marker gene expression 
plot_markers_df <- create_marker_gene_df(
  sce,
  classification_df, 
  marker_genes_file
)
# create a density plot showing the distribution of marker gene expression across classification methods 
marker_density_df <- plot_markers_df |>
  tidyr::pivot_longer(
    cols = ends_with("classification"),
    names_to = "method",
    values_to = "classification"
  ) |> 
  dplyr::mutate(
    method = dplyr::case_when(
      method == "marker_gene_classification" ~ "Marker genes only",
      method == "updated_marker_gene_classification" ~ "Marker genes from 822",
      method == "auc_classification" ~ "AUCell",
      method == "ucell_classification" ~ "UCell",
      method == "blueprint_tumor_classification" ~ "Blueprint",
      method == "updated_singler_classification" ~ "Original",
      method == "updated_singler_blueprint_classification" ~ "Original + Blueprint"
    ),
    classification = dplyr::if_else(classification == "Tumor", "Tumor", "Other")
  )

ggplot(marker_density_df, aes(x = sum_transformed_exp, color = classification)) +
  geom_density() +
  facet_wrap(vars(method), 
             scales = "free_y") +
  labs(
    title = "Marker gene expression",
    x = "Sum of marker genes"
  )

# plot gene set scores for each cell  
geneset_plot_df <- classification_df |> 
  dplyr::select(barcodes, UMAP1, UMAP2, ends_with("classification"), starts_with("mean-")) |> 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("mean"),
    names_to = "geneset",
    values_to = "mean_score"
  ) |> 
  dplyr::mutate(
    geneset = stringr::word(geneset, -1, sep = "-")
  ) |> 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(
    cols = ends_with("classification"),
    names_to = "method",
    values_to = "classification"
  ) |> 
  dplyr::mutate(
    method = dplyr::case_when(
      method == "marker_gene_classification" ~ "Marker genes only",
      method == "updated_marker_gene_classification" ~ "Marker genes from 822",
      method == "auc_classification" ~ "AUCell",
      method == "ucell_classification" ~ "UCell",
      method == "blueprint_tumor_classification" ~ "Blueprint",
      method == "updated_singler_classification" ~ "Original",
      method == "updated_singler_blueprint_classification" ~ "Original + Blueprint"
    ),
    classification = dplyr::if_else(classification == "Tumor", "Tumor", "Other")
    ) 
  
ggplot(geneset_plot_df, aes(x = mean_score, color = classification)) +
  geom_density(bw = 0.05) +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(method), 
             cols = vars(geneset),
             scales = "free_y") +
  labs(
    title = "Gene set scores",
    x = "Mean gene set score"
  )

Looking at these plots, generally Blueprint only has the best separation between tumor cells and all other cells for both gene set scores and marker gene expression. This also seems to mirror the plots shown with AUCell as the classifier.

It looks like we may be mis-classifying some cells when using the original SingleR assignments for SCPCL000822 with or without Blueprint. There is some overlap in the marker gene and gene set scores for the cells that are identified as tumor and other non-tumor cells for both original and original and blueprint.

Conclusions

  • For the most part, all SingleR references identify a similar set of tumor cells. However there are some cells that are only identified in one or two methods making the full set of tumor cells unique across references.
  • All three references identify the same top normal cell types with some overlapping sets.
  • There does not appear to be a consensus between the original SingleR annotations and the new annotations for any of the references.
  • Using SCPCL000822 with tumor and normal labels in combination with Blueprint seems to be the most consistent with using the marker gene based methods for calling tumor cells. Additionally, this reference showed the greatest distinction between tumor cells and all other cells in marker gene expression and gene set scores.
